Part I: Research Question¶
A. Describe the purpose of this data mining report by doing the following:¶
1. Propose one question relevant to a real-world organizational situation that you will answer by using principal component analysis (PCA).¶

“Given that it costs 10 times more to acquire a new customer than to retain an existing one, customer retention has now become even more important than customer acquisition. For many providers, retaining highly profitable customers is the number one business goal. To reduce customer churn, telecommunications companies need to predict which customers are at high risk of churn.” (WGU-D212, 2021)

The company is interested in predicting the customers’ churn probability, while there is usually a big amount of irrelevant data that can be costly to collect and process without adding any value to the purpose of the analysis.

The question to be asked is about the possibility and efficiency of optimizing customer data and reducing its complexity then using this data to predict customers’ Churn, in other words, can we reduce the dimensions of data without affecting the customers’ Churn prediction?

PCA method will be used for dimensionality reduction and to answer this business question.

2. Define one goal of the data analysis. Ensure that your goal is reasonable within the scope of the scenario and is represented in the available data.¶

The objective of the data analysis is to test the use of PCA in order to optimize the data set and reduce the number of features while keeping an amount of variance sufficient for predicting the customers’ churn probability.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------¶
Part II: Method Justification¶
B. Explain the reasons for using PCA by doing the following:¶
1. Explain how PCA analyzes the selected data set. Include expected outcomes.¶

PCA analyzes the data through the following steps:¶

  1. all variables should be accessed on the same ratio level of measurement (Vadapalli,2020)., the original input variables are standardized ( z-scored ) (Loukas,2020), such each original variable has zero mean and unit standard deviation.
  1. Constructing the eigendecomposition of the covariance matrix (in the case of standardized data the covariance is equal to the correlation matrix since the standard deviation of all features is 1) (Loukas,2020).
  1. Eigenvalues are then sorted in a descending order representing decreasing variance in the data (the eigenvalues are equal to the variance) (Loukas,2020).
  1. We may choose how many eigenvalues (components) to proceed with. We will lose some information while ignoring the smaller eigenvalues, but those small values supposed to not create enough impact on the final result, The selected higher eigenvalues will become the dimensions of a new updated feature set. We also form a feature vector, which is a vector matrix consisting of eigenvectors of relative chosen eigenvalues (Vadapalli,2020).
  1. Using the feature vector, we find the principal components of the dataset under analysis. We multiply the transpose of the feature vector with the transpose of the scaled matrix (a scaled version of data after normalisation) to obtain a matrix containing principal components or the reduced PCA space (Vadapalli,2020).
  1. The new reduced PCA space maximizes the variance of the original data (Loukas,2020).
2. Summarize one assumption of PCA.¶

PCA assumes that the principal component with high variance must be more important than the PCs with lower variance (disregarded as noise).

Pearson correlation coefficient framework led to the origin of PCA, and there it was assumed first that the axes with high variance would only be turned into principal components (Vadapalli,2020).

This is done by projecting (dot product) the original data into the reduced PCA space using the eigenvectors of the covariance/correlation matrix aka the principal components (PCs) where reduced PCs space maximizes the variance of the original data.(Loukas,2020)

'''
Custom function , takes 2 arguments as 2 data frames:
1- input features data frame
2- actual target that need to be tested relative to PCA

The output is a series of cross plots , each cross plot is an xplot between two PCs of the input data frame, where points
are colored by :
- actual target that need to be tested relative to PCA
'''

def pc_visual(pc_df,target_df):
#     print(" -  Colored by " + target )
    displayed = [];pair1={};pair2={}
    for n, col1 in enumerate(pc_df.columns):   #enumerating each column of the data, starting from index
        for m, col2 in enumerate(pc_df.columns):
            pair1 = {col1:col2}
            pair2={col2:col1}
            if ((col1 == col2) or (pair1 in displayed) or (pair2 in displayed)):
                continue
            displayed.append(pair1)
            displayed.append(pair2)
            plt.figure(figsize=(6,3))
            ax1=plt.subplot2grid(shape=(1,1),loc=(0,0))
            ax1=plt.scatter(pc_df.loc[:,col1],pc_df.loc[:,col2],c=target_df.iloc[:,0],s=5,cmap='plasma',alpha=0.1) #plotting scatterd plot against the index of the D.F.
#             ax1.grid(True)
            plt.colorbar(ax1)
            plt.title('[Colored by ' + 'Actual '+target+']',fontsize = 9)
            #plt.title(col1+" Vs "+col2+" -  [Colored by " + 'Clusters]' ,fontsize = 9)
            plt.xlabel(col1,fontsize = 8);
            plt.ylabel(col2,fontsize = 8)
            plt.xticks(fontsize = 6)
            plt.yticks(fontsize = 6)
        
            plt.tight_layout()
            plt.show()

5. Summarize the results of your data analysis.¶

PCA is an unsupervised dimensionality reduction technique depending on the variance of input features and maximizing the separation or segregation of observations (variance), regardless of the meaning or the significance of this variance.

But for the purpose of this analysis, some measures had been taken to utilize the PCA technique in order to optimize the data set and reduce the number of features while keeping an amount of variance sufficient for predicting the customers’ churn probability.

The PCA helped to reduce the number of features from 18 to 4 (selected according to elbow method), even though a high amount of data variance has been sacrificed (from 1 to 0.4) but overall, for the purpose of the analysis, the reduced PCs could give a good dimensionality or space for clustering or separating the customers who have higher Chusrn probability and can be used next in predicting this probability.
